Here's where I've gotten with this.

Method 1. I created a class that wraps chess.uci.Engine; when creating it I don't supply it with a concrete Engine but rather with a factory function that generates the Engine. I save this factory function. Then this wrapper class passes any commands like .go(...) onto the current Engine instance. If doing so raises an EngineTerminatedException, then I assert that the old Engine's process.is_alive() is False, and create a new Engine instance using the saved factory function. Then I can re-issue the command that failed. Here is some of the code:

```
class Engine2:
  def __init__(self, factory, pv, threads):
    self.factory = factory
    self.pv = pv
    self.threads = threads
    self.engine = factory(pv, threads)
    assert isinstance(self.engine, U.Engine)
    self.info_handlers = self.engine.info_handlers
  def quit(self, async_callback=None):
    try:
      return self.engine.quit(async_callback)
    except U.EngineTerminatedException:
      return self.engine.terminate(async_callback)
  def is_alive(self):
    return self.engine.is_alive()
  def restart(self):
    assert not self.engine.process.is_alive()
    print("Restarting UCI Engine", file=sys.stderr)
    self.engine = self.factory(self.pv, self.threads)
  ...
  def go(self, searchmoves=None, ponder=False, wtime=None, btime=None, winc=None, binc=None, movestogo=None, depth=None, nodes=None, mate=None, movetime=None, infinite=False, async_callback=None):
    try:
      return self.engine.go(searchmoves, ponder, wtime, btime, winc, binc, movestogo, depth, nodes, mate, movetime, infinite, async_callback)
    except U.EngineTerminatedException:
      self.restart()
      return self.go(searchmoves, ponder, wtime, btime, winc, binc, movestogo, depth, nodes, mate, movetime, infinite, async_callback)
```

This works all right. One perhaps awkward thing is that the Engine isn't re-created when the KeyboardInterrupt happens, but later, when you try to invoke it again for the first time *after* the KeyboardInterrupt.

Method 2. I'm still looking to see if there's some way to catch the interrupt when it happens, and gracefully send a "stop" command to the UCI engine, without having its process be killed and need to be re-generated. So far as I've been able to tell, this would require subclassing concurrent.futures.ThreadPoolExecutor, and may also require using ctypes. I'm not sure if it's possible do this cleanly even then. I'm still looking into it, out of curiosity.

I did try registering my own signal handler for the KeyboardInterrupt, but this doesn't seem to help. You can prevent the interrupt from propagating, but then control isn't returned to the thread that's waiting for the uci.Engine to give a result. If you do propagate the interrupt, then you get the EngineTerminatedException from the UCI Engine. Trying to tell the UCI Engine to "stop" before you propagate the interrupt doesn't work. In that case, waiting for the result from "stop" will itself raise the EngineTerminatedException. (And calling "stop" asynchronously doesn't help. If you propagate the interrupt before waiting for the result from "stop", the UCI Engine process will die just as if no "stop" were involved. If you wait for the result from "stop" before propagating the interrupt, this is the same as issuing the "stop" synchronously.) This is all going from memory of my experimentation, but I think it's right.

I tried to modify Method1 so that we could at least re-generate the Engine when the KeyboardInterrupt happens, rather than when the Engine is next asked to do something. I think that could work, but interestingly in a fragment like this:

```
res = stockfish.go(movetime=60*1000, async_callback=True)
try:
  res.result()
except KeyboardInterrupt:
  print(stockfish.engine.process.is_alive())
  res2=stockfish.stop(async_callback=True)
```
you'll see "True" be printed: the UCI Engine process hasn't yet died when our exception block is called. And if you waited for `res2.result()` (or called `stop` synchronously) before leaving the exception block, you'd get an EngineTerminatedException.

@cpitclaudel:
To use MutatorMath you need “masters”. Masters are interpolatable UFOs, meaning, for each glyph, its outline in each master has the same number and types of points or the same contours. The Ubuntu TTFs were generated in a way that breaks this (when converting from cubic curves in the design sources to quadratic curves for TTF). The UFOs you generated are not interpolatable and therefore cannot be used as masters.

To MutatorMath with the Ubuntu fonts one would need the original design sources that were interpolatable at some point (in this case not the final design) or one would have to manual make the final design sources interpolatable.

The Field is really nothing special, just this

```
Field = namedtuple('Field', ['required', 'type'])
SubSchema = namedtuple('SubSchema', ['required', 'include'])
```
The smart bit is just the translation between one format and the other, but it's also just something like this
```
def build_voluptuous_schema(conf):
    def _process(conf):
        if isinstance(conf, (list, tuple)):
            schema = [_process(c) for c in conf]
        else:
            schema = {}
            for field_name, field in conf.items():
                voluptuous_type = R if field.required else O
                if isinstance(field, SubSchema):
                    schema[voluptuous_type(field_name)] = _process(field.include)
                else:
                    schema[voluptuous_type(field_name)] = field.type
        return schema
```

I just think that in general the current way of declaring the schema is not declarative "enough", and it would make it a lot easy to manipulate with some simple changes...

