This tripped me up today as well. It's worth noting that the slowness only comes up for the backwards pass, when the input is an `ArrayNode`.

I ended up making my own version of stack that avoids the `autograd.numpy.array()` call:
```
def stack(arrays, axis):
  if not arrays:
      raise ValueError('need at least one array to stack')

  shapes = set(arr.shape for arr in arrays)
  if len(shapes) != 1:
      raise ValueError('all input arrays must have the same shape')

  result_ndim = arrays[0].ndim + 1
  if not -result_ndim <= axis < result_ndim:
      raise IndexError('axis {0} out of bounds [-{1}, {1})'.format(axis, result_ndim))
  if axis < 0:
      axis += result_ndim
      
  sl = (slice(None),) * axis + (None,)
  return autograd.numpy.concatenate([arr[sl] for arr in arrays], axis=axis)
```
(This is literally the same function from autograd/numpy, except I removed the line `arrays = [array(arr) for arr in arrays]`.)

It seems like the general fix might be is to allow `autograd.numpy.array()` (at least inside the `stack` functions) to pass through `ArrayNode` objects?

